You would use the colon when assigning a key value pair within  an object, and you would use the `=` sign to assign variables to a name with a keyword of either var, let, or const.  Example of a variable assigned with an `=`:


let foo = [ ];     


 Here I've assigned an empty array to the word foo, now when I call foo anywhere in my code it will return an empty array unless I add to that array then it will return the contents.


An example of an Object with key value pairs would be:


{"key": "value} 


So "key" has a value of "value", separated by a colon. We can also assign our object to a variable like this:


let objectName = {"key" : "value"}


Now whenever we call objectName it will return us an object with key value pairs.


